  "prompt": "Which is the best book of linear algebra?",
  "response": "There are several excellent books on linear algebra, each catering to different audiences and purposes. Here are a few highly regarded titles:\n\n1. **\"Linear Algebra Done Right\" by Sheldon Axler** - This book focuses on the theoretical aspects of linear algebra and emphasizes vector spaces and linear transformations over matrices. It's well-suited for students who want a deep understanding of the subject.\n\n2. **\"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Gilbert Strang** - Strang's book is accessible and practical, making it a great choice for beginners. It includes numerous applications and insights, along with a clear exposition.\n\n3. **\"Matrix Algebra\" by David G. Luenberger and Yeefei Wu** - This book is more focused on matrix theory and provides a strong foundation in that area, which is crucial for many applications in engineering and applied mathematics.\n\n4. **\"Linear Algebra and Its Applications\" by David C. Lay** - This is a popular textbook for undergraduate courses. It balances theory and practical applications, making it useful for students in various fields.\n\n5. **\"Linear Algebra\" by Serge Lang** - A more concise treatment of linear algebra that is rigorous and a bit less accessible for beginners but is highly respected for its clarity and depth.\n\n6. **\"Advanced Linear Algebra\" by David Eisenbud and William Floyd Cachon** - This is ideal for graduate students looking for a more advanced treatment of the subject.\n\nThe best book will depend on your goals, background, and preferred learning style. If you're looking for theory, \"Linear Algebra Done Right\" is great, while \"Introduction to Linear Algebra\" by Strang is excellent for practical applications.",
